            "section": "Books",
            "content": "THE GHOST AT THE FEAST: America and the Collapse of World Order, 1900-1941, by Robert Kagan\n\nRobert Kagan is the most significant writer of the subspecies of the American foreign policy elite that was once notoriously \u2014 and mistakenly \u2014 labeled \u201cneoconservative.\u201d As Kagan has long and justly protested, there is nothing particularly \u201cneo\u201d or \u201cconservative\u201d about America\u2019s attempts to shape the world in its image. The founders saw the nation as \u201cHercules in a cradle.\u201d Thomas Jefferson envisioned a vast \u201cempire for liberty.\u201d William Seward declared America\u2019s purpose was \u201cto renovate the condition of mankind.\u201d For decades, Kagan has tried to persuade his countrymen not to forfeit their geopolitical birthright.\n\nIn a series of nimble polemics, and in expansive, finely wrought historical works, Kagan has spun variations on his theme: America\u2019s unfolding purpose is to be the world\u2019s organizing power, it owes this sense of mission to deeply ingrained American ideals, and the chief threat to this will-to-primacy comes not from without, but from within.\n\nA veteran of the Reagan administration, Kagan rose to prominence in the 1990s, when he co-founded the Project for a New American Century, a think tank devoted to the pursuit of \u201cbenevolent global hegemony.\u201d In \u201cParadise and Power,\u201d published in the early months of the second Iraq war, Kagan argued that the United States \u201cmust live by a double standard\u201d: proclaim a rules-based order, but maintain a monopoly on treaty-breaking and violence to advance human progress. By 2012, when U.S. interventionism seemed to be in tatters, Kagan was determined to stay the course. In \u201cThe World America Made,\u201d Kagan argued that America was not in decline, but in denial. He gamely advanced what some have called the George Bailey doctrine: When the \u201cIt\u2019s a Wonderful Life\u201d protagonist tours a world without him, he encounters a hellscape. America, for Kagan, is the Jimmy Stewart of the world order: If it isn\u2019t there, then \u2014 as the title of Kagan\u2019s last book delicately phrased it \u2014 \u201cthe jungle grows back.\u201d\n\n\u201cThe Ghost at the Feast\u201d is the second volume of a projected trilogy. The first, \u201cDangerous Nation\u201d (2006), focused on the United States getting its own continent in order. The new book spans the era between 1898 and 1941. As the 19th century drew to a close, Kagan writes, \u201cAmericans had no grand international plan and no clear direction.\u201d Other nations were taken aback by how faintly American power registered in their world \u2014 \u201cthe ghost at all our feasts,\u201d per the British diplomat Harold Nicolson. The Spanish-American War is conventionally considered America\u2019s imperial turn, when it acquired its first colony, fought Indigenous rebels overseas and decided, in the words of William James, \u201cto puke up its ancient soul \u2026 in five minutes without a hint of squeamishness.\u201d For Kagan, it was a far more wholesome affair. Business interests in the United States were against the war; the most ardent backers of the interventions were the self-identifying \u201cpopulists.\u201d For Kagan, it is crucial to show that America\u2019s early adventures abroad were not elite conspiracies, but moral undertakings with broad popular support. The United States may not have become a world power in 1898, Kagan claims, but the nation did become more conscious of its capacities.",
