            "title": "A Vital Question for Brazil\u2019s Democracy: Where Were the Police? - The New York Times",
            "published_date": "2023-01-11T19:48:49.000Z",
            "authors": null,
            "description": "Their early inaction in Sunday\u2019s riot shows how security forces can help empower violence and deepen the threat to democracy.",
            "section": "World",
            "content": "As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nTheir early inaction in Sunday\u2019s riot shows how security forces can help empower violence and deepen the threat to democracy.\n\nThe mob attack on Brazil\u2019s democratic institutions in the capital, Bras\u00edlia, on Sunday was a sudden and major test of the country\u2019s resilience. And at least at the start, a conspicuous absence of police security was a factor as supporters of former president Jair Bolsonaro surged to the Congress, Supreme Court and Presidential Palace. The reasons for that delay are not completely clear, but some senior officials are now accusing the capital security forces of delaying more out of intent than confusion. Brazil\u2019s justice minister, Fl\u00e1vio Dino, said that there were far fewer officers present than had been agreed upon in the security plan made days earlier. And one Supreme Court justice has issued an arrest warrant for the top capital security officer. Videos circulated online of the officers who were present appearing to escort protesters on their way to the federal buildings, and pausing to snap selfies with them. By the end of the day, things had changed. New contingents of officers arrived, and they regained control over the capital buildings. Over 1,200 people were detained, more than 700 of whom were accused of having participated in the violence. The authorities have now moved on to arresting those suspected of organizing or financing the riots. Two government security officials are also accused of aiding the riots through criminal negligence or complicity.\n\nBut by the time the arrests began, the damage had been done. Buildings from all three branches of the federal government had been ransacked, and valuable works of art vandalized.The police are usually the first line of response to such mass action, and that gives them tremendous power to affect outcomes. Those early hours were an object lesson in the way that police inaction can empower political violence and exacerbate the threats it poses to democracy. And that may be particularly true in Brazil, where one of the vital questions facing the newly elected government is how much to try to reform or constrain the security sector. Judged by the rioters\u2019 own stated goals, the violent attack in Bras\u00edlia was a failure. The events on Sunday did not lead to a military coup, which many of those present had been calling for over the past 10 weeks. Naunihal Singh, the author of \u201cSeizing Power: The Strategic Logic of Military Coups,\u201d posits that the costs of military coups have become so high, in terms of capital flight, regional sanctions and other forms of international pressure, that it would now be highly unlikely for one to happen in a country like Brazil. Thousands of rioters supporting Jair Bolsonaro, the far-right former president of Brazil, stormed the nation\u2019s Congress, Supreme Court and presidential offices on Jan. 8.\n\u2022 None Anatomy of a Mass Attack: After Mr. Bolsonaro lost the presidential election in October, many believed that the threat of violence from his supporters would recede. After Mr. Bolsonaro lost the presidential election in October, many believed that the threat of violence from his supporters would recede. Here is what went wrong\n\u2022 None The Investigations: Authorities face Authorities face several major questions as they piece together how rioters briefly seized the seats of Brazil\u2019s government.\n\u2022 None Digital Playbook: Misinformation researchers are studying how the internet was used ahead of the riots in Brazil. Misinformation researchers are studying how the internet was used ahead of the riots in Brazil. Many are drawing a comparison to the Jan. 6 attack\n\u2022 None The Role of the Police: Their early inaction in the riot shows Their early inaction in the riot shows how security forces can help empower violence and deepen the threat to democracy. Indeed, Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva remains secure in the presidency, and Mr. Bolsonaro remains in Florida. And the attack has drawn widespread opposition from the public and condemnation from lawmakers. On Monday, the heads of all three branches of the government issued a rare joint statement condemning the violence. It is possible that the backlash to Sunday\u2019s events will discredit Mr. Bolsonaro\u2019s supporters and drain energy from their movement. Yanilda Mar\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez, a Harvard University political scientist who studies policing and democracy in the Americas, noted that opposition to the violence in Bras\u00edlia within the government, public opinion and news media commentary has been far more unified than the reaction to the Jan. 6 attacks in the United States two years ago. If that opinion holds, and the protest movement fractures under the disapproval, then the risk of further violence would be fairly low.\n\nBut that could change, particularly as the government begins prosecuting the hundreds of people arrested for participating in the riot. The new administration \u201chas to prosecute these people, and is going to prosecute these people,\u201d said Amy Erica Smith, a political scientist at the University of Iowa who studies Brazilian politics and democracy. \u201cBut prosecuting them may also be destabilizing.\u201d It\u2019s important, too, to know that a sudden military coup is not the only way that political violence can undermine democracy. The police in Brazil have a history of using strategic inaction as a political tool, Ms. Gonz\u00e1lez said. Her research found that in S\u00e3o Paulo in the 1980s, for instance, the police let riots unfold during a time of economic crisis in order to generate a sense of panic in society that would put pressure on politicians. And in 2013, after the mayor of S\u00e3o Paulo delayed overtime payments to the local military police, they were deliberately lax in policing a major cultural festival, leading to a spike in crime and a slew of bad headlines for the mayor. Now, she sees a risk that pro-Bolsonaro factions within the police or other security services could \u201cstand with their arms crossed\u201d rather than stopping political violence in the future. There are allegations that deliberate inaction already played a role in Sunday\u2019s riot. On Tuesday, Alexandre de Moraes, a Brazilian Supreme Court justice (and a polarizing figure in his own right, who has been accused of severely overstepping his authority), said that investigators had found evidence that security officials knew violence was brewing but did not stop it. He issued an arrest warrant for Anderson Torres, the man effectively in charge of security for the capital, in response to a request by the federal police. \u201cThe risk is of a slow erosion of institutions and norms,\u201d Ms. Gonz\u00e1lez said. In the worst-case scenario, bottom-up political violence, combined with targeted inaction from elements within the police or other security services, could add up to \u201ca slow-building coup, almost an everyday coup.\u201d One reason for that kind of strategic inaction might be support for Mr. Bolsonaro, who is widely believed to be the preferred candidate of the police and military rank and file. But another, perhaps more likely, motivation is that many within the security establishment fear that Mr. Lula's policies could threaten the security forces\u2019 status, privileges or immunities.\n\nMr. Bolsonaro embraced the military and the police as a matter of political identity as well as policy. As a legislator, he dedicated his vote to impeach Dilma Rousseff, Mr. Lula\u2019s handpicked successor, to the man who had tortured her when she was imprisoned under the military dictatorship. As president, he expanded immunity for police officers who used deadly force, increased military pensions and appointed military officials to powerful cabinet positions. \u201cSecurity forces have gotten away with a lot of things in recent years. Police violence has gone mostly unchecked,\u201d said Christoph Harig, a research fellow at Technical University Braunschweig in Germany who studies policing and civilian-military relations in Brazil. \u201cThere are so many cases of innocents being killed, mostly by police, or sometimes the army on internal missions, where those killers have gotten away with very lenient sentences. It\u2019s this impunity that\u2019s prevalent in a lot of the Brazilian police and military.\u201d Mr. Lula does not share that political affinity for the security forces, and has signaled that he wants to limit the role of the military in politics. Many wonder how far he will go in reversing Bolsonaro-era policies, or whether he might try to go further, as he did in 2009, when he proposed a truth commission into dictatorship-era torture and other crimes and a review of the law that provided amnesty for them. (He was forced to drop the proposal after multiple senior military officials threatened to resign in protest.) Mr. Harig noted that military officials in Bras\u00edlia defended the pro-coup demonstrators as \u201cpeaceful protesters\u201d and allowed them to camp outside military headquarters as their numbers grew over the past 10 weeks. That effectively sheltered the pro-coup movement, though the military leadership itself refused to actually support or conduct a coup. That may pose an object lesson to the government, Mr. Harig believes, on the importance of remaining on good terms with the military. He cited Mr. Lula\u2019s appointment of Jos\u00e9 Mucio as the defense secretary, a civilian but one widely seen as friendly to military interests, as a sign that such pressure had been effective. \u201cI think these protest camps have been sort of useful idiots for the military in recent weeks,\u201d Mr. Harig said. \u201cThey won\u2019t accept any threats to their institutional privileges.\u201d Ms. Smith, the Iowa professor, said that she thinks Mr. Lula will be able to shore up enough support within the military and police to crack down on violent protests as needed. But if he doesn\u2019t, and the protests expand into attacks on crucial infrastructure like oil refineries, becoming a kind of low-level insurgency, she believes that could be politically destabilizing \u2014 and perhaps fatal to his presidency.",
