            "content": "Gov. Kathy Hochul said she nominated Judge Hector LaSalle to become the state\u2019s top judge because he was the right person to \u201cbring a fractured court together.\u201d\n\nAs a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nGov. Kathy Hochul has not given up on her nomination of Hector LaSalle to lead the state Court of Appeals, but the Legislature could refuse to approve him.\n\nAllegations of racism and racial pandering. Complaints about left-wing insurgents and right-wing courts. And dire forecasts about the fate of abortion access, organized labor and legal protections for criminal defendants. It is the kind of political firestorm that typically accompanies the nomination of prospective U.S. Supreme Court justices. But this time, it is playing out in New York, in an ugly squabble that leaves Gov. Kathy Hochul, a Democrat, at risk of becoming the first governor in New York to have her nominee for the state\u2019s top judge get rejected \u2014 at the hands of her own party. Ms. Hochul\u2019s choice of Hector D. LaSalle, an appellate court justice and a former prosecutor, as her nominee for chief judge of the Court of Appeals, the state\u2019s highest court, has turned into an unexpectedly fierce battle, with an emboldened Democratic Legislature standing in the governor\u2019s way. When he was on the short list for the job last fall, the New York State Bar Association gave Justice LaSalle its highest rating, \u201cwell qualified.\u201d After his nomination, the organization\u2019s president described him as an \u201coutstanding choice,\u201d praising his \u201cremarkable intellect and deep practical knowledge of the courts.\u201d\n\nBut if the lawmakers vote as they have pledged to in recent weeks, Justice LaSalle appears to face near-certain defeat in the State Senate, which is responsible for confirming nominees \u2014 if he is even able to make it past the chamber\u2019s Judiciary Committee. The committee is expected to consider his nomination in the coming days, ahead of a Jan. 22 deadline. At issue is the judge\u2019s voting record, with a critical mass of Democrats in Albany \u2014 who hold a supermajority in the Legislature \u2014 saying he is too conservative to lead the seven-member court. The dispute has pitted a crop of Latino and other minority lawmakers \u2014 who embrace him as the state\u2019s prospective first Latino chief judge \u2014 against left-leaning lawmakers, who say that his decisions reveal stances taken against unions, reproductive choice and the rights of defendants. Justice LaSalle\u2019s defenders say the opposition has mischaracterized a handful of the judge\u2019s cases, and other Democrats have praised both his record and judicial approach. \u201cIn his 14 years on the bench and throughout his distinguished legal career in public service, Justice Hector LaSalle has established a strong record as a brilliant lawyer and a scrupulously fair and thoughtful jurist,\u201d said Eric Gonzalez, the Brooklyn district attorney, in a statement supporting the nomination. The intraparty battle is bound to test Ms. Hochul\u2019s political strength against a State Senate that has increasingly lurched to the left and appears eager to assert its growing sway in the State Capitol. It has also raised questions about how Ms. Hochul, who appeared blindsided by the opposition, may have misjudged the shifting political winds in Albany and whether she failed to lock up sufficient support for Justice LaSalle in advance.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s a reflection of frustration on the left with some of the decisions coming out of the federal courts,\u201d said Jonathan Lippman, a former chief judge for the court who retired in 2015 and has voiced support for Justice LaSalle. \u201cBut you can\u2019t compare apples to oranges.\u201d Opposition to Justice LaSalle\u2019s nomination has focused on several appellate cases where he joined the majority opinion, but did not write it. Office of Governor Kathy Hochul, via Associated Press Justice LaSalle, 54, is the presiding justice of the Appellate Division of the Second Judicial Department of the New York State Supreme Court, which handles civil and criminal appeals from Brooklyn, Queens, Staten Island, Westchester and a half-dozen other counties. He was elected as a State Supreme Court justice in 2008 in Suffolk County, and in 2014, Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo appointed him associate justice of the appellate court he now leads. Justice LaSalle\u2019s critics have pointed to several appellate cases as evidence that he is conservative, pro-prosecutor, anti-union and anti-abortion. In those cases, the judge joined \u2014 but did not write \u2014 the majority opinion, making it difficult to discern his personal legal reasoning. In a 2014 decision, People v. Corbin, Justice LaSalle joined a majority denying a defendant\u2019s appeal of a conviction on a weapons possession charge, on the grounds that the defendant had knowingly waived the right to an appeal when he pleaded guilty to the crime two years earlier. The defendant had argued, after his plea, that the original police search had been illegal; the appeals court said that the trial record showed that the trial judge and his lawyer had correctly advised the defendant that he could not retroactively challenge evidence once he entered a guilty plea. Some organized labor groups have objected to Justice LaSalle\u2019s 2015 vote in a defamation case that arose from a lawsuit filed by Cablevision against the communications workers union and two union members over statements made in a town-hall meeting.\n\nA lower court had dismissed the case under a state law that prohibits companies from suing unions and their representatives for labor-related activities. The appeals panel agreed that the suit against the union itself must be dismissed, but said it could proceed against union representatives who had been acting on their own. In 2017, Justice LaSalle joined a unanimous opinion that ordered the New York attorney general to narrow a subpoena issued to the operator of anti-abortion \u201ccrisis pregnancy centers.\u201d The subpoena was issued as part of an investigation by former Attorney General Eric Schneiderman into whether the operator, Evergreen Association, Inc., was engaged in the unauthorized practice of medicine, and sought information about the organization\u2019s promotional literature, corporate structure and staff. Evergreen challenged the subpoena as a politically motivated attack and sought to have it quashed entirely. The opinion held that some of the attorney general\u2019s demands were too broad and infringed on the organization\u2019s First Amendment rights. \u201cThere is no question that the attorney general\u2019s investigation is of the utmost importance to protecting the health and safety of women,\u201d the opinion says. \u201cHowever, it is equally important that such investigation be carried out with respect and sensitivity to the constitutional rights of those involved.\u201d Justice LaSalle\u2019s defenders have said that these cases hinged on procedural and legal matters and that the rulings did not reflect the justice\u2019s underlying beliefs. The cases \u201cdo not stand for anything that the progressives say they stand for,\u201d said Vincent Bonventre, a professor at Albany Law School who follows the Court of Appeals. \u201cI don\u2019t know that he\u2019s conservative. I would say that he\u2019s not liberal. He\u2019s probably pretty moderate.\u201d Jay Jacobs, the state Democratic Party chair, said that he believed the battle over Justice LaSalle had more to do with political flexing than with the judge\u2019s legal philosophy. \u201cThe progressive left, the very progressive left, the far left, as I refer to them, determined that they wanted to use this as, in my judgment, a power play,\u201d said Mr. Jacobs, who has repeatedly come under fire from left-wing lawmakers for his stewardship of the party.\n\nMr. Jacobs added that he felt that recent election results \u2014 in particular last summer\u2019s primary, in which Ms. Hochul cruised past a progressive challenger, Jumaane Williams \u2014 gave her the right to choose whom she pleases. Some political consultants wondered why the governor did not use her leverage to help assure Mr. LaSalle\u2019s nomination and avoid an ugly public battle. The nomination was announced on Dec. 22, when the Legislature had returned to Albany to give itself a $32,000 pay raise \u2014 a move that required the governor\u2019s approval and could have been used to help her with Mr. LaSalle. By then, it was already clear that the process to replace Judge DiFiore, who was reviled by many left-wing Democrats, could devolve into a bitter fight. A group of 20 Senate Democrats indicated that they preferred a candidate who had been a civil rights lawyer or public defender. Justice LaSalle was neither; he had previously been a bureau chief in the Suffolk County district attorney\u2019s office and an assistant attorney general. The governor, however, ultimately chose him, seeing him as one of the most qualified candidates on the short list and his nomination as an opportunity to elevate a Latino to the upper echelons of state government, according to Hochul officials. The Senate must vote to accept or reject him within 30 days of his nomination. But first the judiciary committee, dominated by Democrats, must hold hearings. \u201cI don\u2019t think the nominee has the votes,\u201d said State Senator Brad Hoylman, a Democrat who chairs the committee. Ms. Stewart-Cousins also cast doubt on Mr. LaSalle\u2019s prospects, saying last week in a podcast interview with Gotham Gazette, \u201cI do not see this ending in the way that the governor wished it would.\u201d\n\nThe sheer numbers don\u2019t seem to favor Mr. LaSalle at this moment: The Judiciary recently expanded from 15 to 19 members, a change that Senate Democrats have said was routine, but that Mr. LaSalle\u2019s defenders saw as a plot to stack the committee with \u201cno\u201d votes. If the judge\u2019s nomination reaches the floor, at least a dozen of the 42 Democrats in the 63-seat State Senate have indicated that they would vote against confirming him \u2014 meaning that Ms. Hochul may have to rely on Republicans. \u201cOur conference believes he should get a fair hearing,\u201d said Senator Rob Ortt, the Republican who serves as minority leader. The governor has said she has no intention of withdrawing her nomination. \u201cI selected the very best person; Hector LaSalle has an exceptional record,\u201d Ms. Hochul said in Manhattan on Friday. \u201cHe\u2019ll be the person that\u2019ll bring a fractured court together, he\u2019ll be fair, he\u2019ll be just.\u201d A contingent of Latino leaders, including Representatives Adriano Espaillat and Nydia Vel\u00e1zquez, have also rallied passionately around Justice LaSalle, organizing a Latinos for LaSalle coalition. They see Justice LaSalle\u2019s nomination as a major milestone in a state with a dearth of Latino representation at a statewide level, but it has also pitted them against a crop of mostly younger, more left-leaning Latino officials who have vocally opposed him. \u201cTo have the first Latino and Puerto Rican nominated, and to have his record distorted the way it\u2019s been distorted, I think is unfair,\u201d said Luis Sep\u00falveda, a Democrat from the Bronx who is Puerto Rican and a member of the Judiciary Committee. \u201cI can\u2019t say blindly that this guy is crazy conservative the way they\u2019re trying to picture him.\u201d For his part, Judge Lippman seemed disconsolate about the characterizations of Justice LaSalle as a conservative, which he said is \u201cnothing like the person that I know.\u201d",
