end of the day, he broke his rule 164 times.\n\n10. And finally, with one tweak, you can take professional-looking photos on your iPhone. When people think of smartphone photographs, they often are picturing selfies, on-the-go snaps or filtered images meant for social media. But some of the most popular phones now come equipped with pretty good cameras. And, if you\u2019re really looking to elevate your shots, consider using the format built for the pros: RAW.\n\nEditing a RAW file requires more work, but doing so also allows a photographer to have more control of the light and color in the image after it has been captured. And, in some cases, a RAW file will have enough pixels so that a significantly cropped photo can still look sharp. Your Evening Briefing is posted at 6 p.m. Eastern. Want to catch up on past briefings? You can browse them here. What did you like? What do you want to see here? Let us know at briefing@nytimes.com. Here are today\u2019s Mini Crossword, Spelling Bee and Wordle. If you\u2019re in the mood to play more, find all our games here.",
